    dek: `New filmmakers pour their budget into the camera and treat sound as an afterthought — a $30 shotgun mic bolted on at the last minute. It's the single most common, most damaging mistake in indie film. Because here's the truth audiences prove every day: they'll forgive a rough image, but they'll switch off bad sound in seconds.`,
    seoTitle: "Why Sound Is Half Your Film: Production Sound Basics | Filmmaker Genius",
    seoDesc: "Production sound basics — why bad audio loses an audience faster than a rough image, why fixing it in post is a myth, and what good location sound really means. Chapter 1 of Production Sound Recording.",
    body: `<p>There's a well-worn saying among editors: "sound is half the picture." It sounds like a nice slogan until you watch it happen. Show an audience a beautifully shot film with muffled, echoey, hiss-filled dialogue and they'll call it amateur and drift away. Show them a modestly shot film with clean, crisp, intelligible sound and they'll stay locked in. Audiences will strain to follow a grainy image, but the instant they have to <em>work</em> to understand what someone's saying, the spell breaks and they reach for their phone. Sound isn't the technical afterthought; it's half of what the audience actually experiences — and on a low-budget film it's the cheapest, biggest quality upgrade available to you.</p>

<h2>"Fix it in post" is a myth</h2>

<p>The most expensive words in filmmaking are "we'll fix it in post." With sound, this is close to a fantasy. Post-production audio tools can polish and sweeten a decent recording, but they cannot un-ring a bell: they can't remove the air-conditioning hum baked into a take, un-echo a voice recorded in a tiled bathroom, or conjure clean dialogue from a mic that was six feet away. What isn't captured cleanly on the day is often gone forever, and your alternatives are ugly — either live with bad audio or drag your actors back for <strong>ADR</strong> (re-recording lines in a studio), which is expensive, hard to match, and rarely as alive as the original performance. The professional mindset is the opposite of "fix it in post": <strong>get it right on set</strong>, because that's the only place most of it can be gotten right at all.</p>

<h2>What "good sound" actually means</h2>

<p>So what are we chasing across this whole course? Good production sound comes down to a few clear goals — everything else is technique in service of these:</p>

<ul class="spec-list">
  <li><b>Clean.</b> Free of unwanted noise — no hum, hiss, traffic, wind, or room echo fighting the voice.</li>
  <li><b>Clear and intelligible.</b> Every word of dialogue is easy to understand without effort. That's the whole job, most of the time.</li>
  <li><b>Close and present.</b> The mic is close enough that the voice sounds full and immediate, not distant and hollow.</li>
  <li><b>Consistent.</b> Levels and tone match from take to take and shot to shot, so it cuts together smoothly.</li>
  <li><b>Well-documented and delivered.</b> Recorded at proper levels, labeled, and handed to post with the notes the editor needs (Chapter 11).</li>
</ul>

<div class="pullquote">Audiences will strain to follow a rough image, but the moment they have to work to understand what someone's saying, the spell breaks. Sound isn't the afterthought — it's half of what they actually experience.</div>

<p>The rest of this course is how to hit those goals: the gear, the mics, the boom and the lav, controlling your environment, and delivering to post. But the mindset shift in this chapter is the most important thing here. Decide, right now, that sound is not the thing you'll worry about later — it's a first-class citizen on your set, worth its own dedicated person and its own attention on every take. Make that decision and your films will immediately sound more professional than most of the indie work out there, which is still, astonishingly, treating sound as an afterthought.</p>

<div class="callout">
  <div class="callout-label">◆ From the set</div>
  <p>If you have a tiny budget and must choose where to spend, I'll say something that sounds heretical: put money into <em>sound</em> before you upgrade the camera. A modern budget camera looks great; audiences have made peace with imperfect images. But they have zero tolerance for dialogue they can't understand. A decent mic, a recordist who cares, and a quiet set will do more for how "professional" your film feels than a fancier lens ever will. The cheapest path to looking like you know what you're doing runs straight through the audio.</p>
</div>`,
