    dek: `Booming looks like the easiest job on set — just hold a pole. It's actually a real craft: getting the mic as close as possible to the actor, pointed exactly right, while staying invisible to the camera and the light. Master the boom and you have the best-sounding dialogue tool in film.`,
    seoTitle: "How to Boom a Scene: Boom Mic Technique | Filmmaker Genius",
    seoDesc: "How to boom a scene — positioning the boom mic, pointing at the mouth, staying out of frame and shadow, and following dialogue. The core skill of the boom operator. Chapter 5 of Production Sound Recording.",
    body: `<p>The boom is the preferred way to record dialogue on professional sets, because it delivers the fullest, most natural voice — a well-boomed line sounds like a person in a room, warm and present, in a way a lav clipped to a chest rarely matches. But that quality depends entirely on technique. The boom operator's whole job is a continuous balancing act: get the mic as close to the actor's mouth as humanly possible, aimed precisely at them, <em>without</em> the mic or its shadow ever entering the frame. Every rule of booming flows from that tension between "close and pointed" and "unseen."</p>

<h2>Position: overhead, close, and pointed at the mouth</h2>

<p>The default and best boom position is <strong>from above</strong> — the mic held over the actors, just out of the top of frame, angled down toward their mouths. Overhead is preferred because it captures the voice cleanly while pointing away from noisy floors and reflective surfaces. When an overhead isn't possible (a very wide shot, a low ceiling), you boom <strong>from below</strong>, pointing up at the mouth from just under frame. Either way the principles are the same:</p>

<ul class="spec-list">
  <li><b>As close as the frame allows.</b> Get the mic right to the edge of the shot — the closer, the fuller and cleaner the voice. Have the operator find that edge with the camera department before the take.</li>
  <li><b>Point at the mouth.</b> A shotgun mic hears what it's aimed at, so the tip must point directly at the speaker's mouth, not their chest or the space beside them. Aim is everything.</li>
  <li><b>Angle down (or up), never flat.</b> Pointing slightly down from overhead (or up from below) keeps the mic aimed at the voice and away from background noise sources.</li>
  <li><b>Lead the dialogue.</b> In a two-hander, the operator subtly swings the mic to favor whoever is speaking, arriving a beat before their line — anticipating, not chasing.</li>
  <li><b>Mind the wind and handling.</b> Windshield on outdoors, and hold the pole still and quiet — grip noise and cable rattle travel straight into the mic.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Staying invisible: frame and shadow</h2>

<p>The two ways a boom ruins a take are getting <em>in the shot</em> and casting a <em>shadow</em> into it — and the second catches people out constantly. The operator must know exactly where the top of frame is (get the camera operator to show them the boundary) and ride the mic just above it, dipping in as close as they dare without crossing the line. Just as important, they must watch for the boom's <strong>shadow</strong>: a hard light can throw the mic's silhouette onto a wall or an actor's face even when the mic itself is well out of frame, and that shadow is just as ruinous. This is why sound and lighting have to talk to each other — the operator finds an angle that's close and pointed but where the shadow falls somewhere harmless. It's a genuinely athletic, focused job: holding a pole steady overhead for a long take, arms burning, tracking the dialogue, watching the frame line and the shadow, all while staying silent. Respect the boom operator; a great one is the reason your dialogue sounds like a movie. And if you're a one-person sound crew, a cheap <strong>C-stand</strong> can hold the boom in a fixed position for a static shot — not as responsive as a human, but far better than a camera-top mic.</p>

<div class="pullquote">The boom operator's whole craft is one balancing act — get the mic as close to the mouth as possible, pointed exactly right, while keeping both the mic and its shadow out of the frame.</div>

<div class="callout">
  <div class="callout-label">◆ From the set</div>
  <p>The killer nobody expects is the boom <em>shadow</em>. The operator is proud that the mic is nowhere near the frame — and meanwhile a hard key light is painting a big fuzzy sausage-shadow of the mic right across the back wall. It gets missed because everyone's watching the frame edge, not the walls. So before a take I do a quick shadow check: I have the operator get into position and I scan the whole set, especially bright walls and the actors' faces, for the mic's silhouette. Ten seconds, and it saves a whole scene where the "invisible" mic was visible the entire time.</p>
</div>`,
