    time: "8 min",
    moduleKey: "core",
    kicker: "Core Craft",
    dek: `Dialogue is the reason production sound exists. Getting a clean line once is easy; getting clean, consistent, <em>matchable</em> dialogue across every take and every angle of a scene is the real craft — and it's what lets the editor cut freely without the sound falling apart. Here's how to deliver dialogue the edit can actually use.`,
    seoTitle: "Recording Dialogue On Set: Clean, Clear & Consistent | Filmmaker Genius",
    seoDesc: "Recording dialogue on set — getting clean, clear, consistent, and matchable dialogue take after take, favoring perspective, and giving the editor options. Chapter 7 of Production Sound Recording.",
    body: `<p>By now you have the tools: the right mic, close, at a good level, on a quiet set. This chapter is about using them to serve the thing that matters most — clear, consistent dialogue — and about the subtle craft of making that dialogue <em>cut together</em>. Because a film scene isn't one recording; it's a wide, some mediums, and close-ups, all shot separately and assembled. If the sound quality jumps around between those angles, the scene falls apart in the edit even if each take sounded fine on its own. Consistency is the quiet superpower of a good recordist.</p>

<h2>Consistency: the takes have to match</h2>

<p>The editor will cut from the wide to the close-up mid-sentence, and the audience must not hear the join. That means the sound across every setup in a scene needs to feel like one continuous space. Your habits for getting there:</p>

<ul class="spec-list">
  <li><b>Keep mic distance consistent.</b> Try to hold the boom roughly the same distance from the actor across the wide and the tight — wildly different distances make the voice jump from close to hollow between cuts.</li>
  <li><b>Keep your levels steady.</b> Don't dramatically re-ride gain between takes of the same scene; consistent levels make the tracks match and the editor's job possible.</li>
  <li><b>Get every angle's audio.</b> Record good sound on <em>every</em> setup, even the ones you think you'll cut away from — you never know which take the edit will use, and a great picture take with bad sound is a heartbreak.</li>
  <li><b>Watch for changing background.</b> If the fridge kicks on for take 3 but not take 1, they won't cut together. Keep the environment (Chapter 8) as constant as the performance.</li>
  <li><b>Note the good takes.</b> Log which takes had clean sound and which had a problem (a plane, a stumble) so the editor knows where the usable audio is (Chapter 11).</li>
</ul>

<h2>Perspective, and giving the editor options</h2>

<p>There's a subtle refinement beyond raw consistency: <strong>perspective</strong>. Audio has a sense of distance, and ideally it loosely matches the shot — a wide shot can sound a touch more open and roomy, a tight close-up a touch more intimate and present, because that's how our ears expect space to behave. You don't want extremes (a cavernous wide cut against a super-tight close-up jars), but a gentle perspective shift, achieved by adjusting boom distance with the frame, adds realism. In practice, though, <em>consistency beats perfect perspective</em> on a low-budget shoot — when in doubt, keep it matchable. Beyond the scene itself, the professional habit is to <strong>give the editor and sound team options</strong>: run the boom and lavs together so there's a choice of tracks, capture a clean take with no overlapping dialogue where possible (so lines can be trimmed and rearranged), and grab any problem line again as a <strong>wild line</strong> (recorded off-camera, just audio) if a plane flew over the good performance. Every extra clean option you hand to post is a problem they won't have to solve with expensive ADR. And underpinning all of it is the recordist's constant question, take after take: <em>"Was that clean and usable?"</em> — because catching a problem now, while you can still do another take, is the entire job. Get clean, get it consistent, get options, and your dialogue will carry the film.</p>

<div class="pullquote">A scene isn't one recording — it's a wide, some mediums, and close-ups, assembled. If the sound jumps between them, the scene falls apart in the edit even if each take sounded fine alone. Consistency is the quiet superpower.</div>

<div class="callout">
  <div class="callout-label">◆ From the set</div>
  <p>The question I ask myself after literally every take is the whole job: "Was that clean and usable?" Not "was it okay" — <em>usable</em>, cuttable, free of the plane and the stumble and the bump. If the answer is no, I speak up right then and ask for another, because that's the only moment it's fixable. The most expensive habit in indie film is nodding along to a take you know had a problem because you don't want to slow things down — and then discovering in the edit that the best performance is unusable. Ten seconds of "can we get one more clean one?" beats a month of ADR.</p>
</div>`,
