    desc: "Fighting background noise, echo, and wind before they ruin a take",
    time: "8 min",
    moduleKey: "core",
    kicker: "Core Craft",
    dek: `Your microphone is honest to a fault — it records the fridge, the traffic, the echo off the tiled wall, and the wind, right alongside the dialogue. The best mic technique in the world can't fully undo a noisy room. So the real skill is controlling the space <em>before</em> you record, so the mic only hears what you want.`,
    seoTitle: "Controlling Set Noise: Acoustics, Echo & Wind | Filmmaker Genius",
    seoDesc: "Controlling set noise for clean recordings — killing background hum, traffic, air conditioning, echo, and wind before they ruin a take. How to scout and treat a location for sound. Chapter 8 of Production Sound Recording.",
    body: `<p>Here's a humbling fact: on most amateur productions, the sound isn't ruined by bad gear or bad technique — it's ruined by <em>the room</em>. An air conditioner nobody thought to switch off, a buzzing fridge, traffic through a single-pane window, a hard-walled space that turns every voice to echo, or wind battering an outdoor mic. Your microphone can't tell the difference between these and the dialogue; it captures it all. And unlike the mic and levels, much of this can't be fixed later. So a huge part of the sound job happens before "action" — it's <em>preventative</em>, controlling the environment so the mic only has clean voice to catch.</p>

<h2>Kill the noise sources</h2>

<p>Most location noise comes from a short list of usual suspects, and the good news is that many are switchable-off or avoidable if you look for them:</p>

<ul class="spec-list">
  <li><b>Turn off the machines.</b> Air conditioning, heating, fridges, freezers, fans, fluorescent light hum, computers, dishwashers. Walk the room and switch off everything that makes a sound — and put a note to turn the fridge back on after.</li>
  <li><b>Beat the traffic and neighbors.</b> Close windows, choose the quiet side of a building, and schedule around the noisy times. If a plane or a truck passes, hold the take and go again — don't record over it.</li>
  <li><b>Control the humans.</b> A firm "quiet on set" and "rolling" before every take, phones on silent, crew still and silent. Rustling crew and side chatter end up on the track.</li>
  <li><b>Watch continuity of sound.</b> If you turned the fridge off for the wide, keep it off for the close-up — noise that changes between takes won't cut together (Chapter 7).</li>
  <li><b>Listen first.</b> Before you commit to a location, stand in it silently with headphones and <em>listen</em>. The ears you bring to a recce save the day you'd have lost on set.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Echo and wind: the two you can't remove</h2>

<p>Two enemies deserve special attention because they're the least fixable in post. The first is <strong>echo / reverb</strong> — hard, bare, empty rooms (tiled bathrooms, stairwells, empty halls) bounce sound so the voice arrives smeared and hollow. You can't remove echo from a recording; you can only avoid creating it. The fix is to <em>deaden the room</em>: get the mic closer (proximity beats reflections), and bring soft, sound-absorbing material into the space — moving blankets, duvets, curtains, mattresses, even coats — hung on the reflective walls just out of frame. A blanket fort around your actor sounds ridiculous and works brilliantly. The second is <strong>wind</strong> outdoors, which hits the mic as a low, roaring rumble that buries everything. The defense is layered wind protection: a foam windscreen for light breeze, and for real wind a furry <strong>"dead cat" / blimp</strong> over the mic (never shoot exteriors without one), plus using the body of a car, a wall, or a person to shield the mic from the gusts. Both echo and wind share the same lesson as this whole chapter: you win the fight <em>before</em> you press record, by shaping the environment, because once it's baked into the take it's there for good. Control the space, and the mic will reward you with clean sound.</p>

<div class="pullquote">On most amateur films the sound isn't ruined by the gear — it's ruined by the room. The fridge, the echo, the wind. Your mic can't tell them from the dialogue, so you win the fight before "action," not after.</div>

<div class="callout">
  <div class="callout-label">◆ From the set</div>
  <p>My first move walking into any interior location isn't unpacking gear — it's standing dead still with my eyes closed for thirty seconds, just <em>listening</em>. The fridge I didn't notice. The AC. The buzzing dimmer. The traffic through the window. The echo bouncing off bare walls. Every one of those is a problem I can solve <em>now</em> — unplug the fridge, kill the AC, throw a blanket on the wall — but only if I hear it before I'm rolling. Amateurs hear the noise for the first time in the edit. Pros hear it during the recce and quietly make it go away.</p>
</div>`,
