    dek: `You captured great audio all day — but if it arrives in the edit as a heap of cryptically-named files with no notes, half of it might as well not exist. The last job of production sound is delivery: organized, labeled, synced, and documented so the people in post can actually find and use what you recorded.`,
    seoTitle: "Sound for Post-Production: The Sound Report & Handoff | Filmmaker Genius",
    seoDesc: "Delivering production sound to post — the sound report, file naming and organization, sync, and the notes the editor needs so your location audio is usable. Chapter 11 of Production Sound Recording.",
    body: `<p>Production sound doesn't end when you stop recording; it ends when the edit and sound teams have everything they need in a form they can use. This is the unglamorous, deeply important last mile — and it's where a lot of otherwise-good indie sound falls down. A folder of files called <code>ZOOM0001.wav</code> through <code>ZOOM0342.wav</code>, with no indication of what scene, take, or mic each one is, turns your careful day into a treasure hunt. Great delivery is mostly about <em>documentation and organization</em>, and it's easy once you build the habit.</p>

<h2>The sound report and file organization</h2>

<p>The traditional deliverable is the <strong>sound report</strong> — a log, kept as you shoot, of what's on each file. On a pro set it's detailed; on an indie set even a simple version is transformative. Alongside it, how you name and organize the files is half the battle:</p>

<ul class="spec-list">
  <li><b>Log scene, shot, and take.</b> For each recording, note the scene/slate number, take, and which channel is which mic (boom on 1, lav on 2). This is what lets post match audio to picture.</li>
  <li><b>Flag the good and the bad.</b> Mark the <strong>circled takes</strong> (the ones the director liked / that were clean) and note problems ("take 3 — plane"). The editor goes straight to the usable material.</li>
  <li><b>Name files meaningfully.</b> Where your recorder allows, name files by scene/take rather than leaving auto-numbers. If not, the sound report bridges the gap.</li>
  <li><b>Label the specials.</b> Clearly mark room tone, wild lines, and wild effects (Chapter 9) so they don't get lost among the takes.</li>
  <li><b>Keep the folder structured and backed up.</b> Organize by day/scene, and back up the audio immediately — a lost card is a lost shoot day. Redundant copies, always.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Sync, formats, and closing the loop</h2>

<p>Because most film uses dual-system sound (Chapter 4), the other delivery essential is making <strong>sync</strong> painless. Every take should be slated (the clapperboard) so picture and sound can be lined up — modern software syncs automatically from the clap or from matching timecode, but only if you gave it the reference. A take with no slate and no timecode is a manual sync headache, so slate everything, even pickups (and if you truly can't slate, a hand-clap in frame works in a pinch). On the technical side, deliver <strong>uncompressed WAV files</strong> at the project's sample rate (commonly 48kHz), never lossy formats like MP3 — you want the full quality you worked to capture. Then close the loop by actually <em>talking to post</em>: a quick handoff conversation or a note in your report telling the editor what to watch for ("Scene 14 lav dropped, use the boom track"; "the café ambience is in the wild folder") saves them hours of guesswork. This final chapter of your job is a courtesy to your future self and your collaborators, and it's the difference between audio that gets used and audio that gets abandoned. You did the hard work on set; don't let it evaporate at the handoff. Label it, sync it, back it up, and hand it over with a map — and every clean take you fought for will actually make it into the film.</p>

<div class="pullquote">You captured great audio all day — but a folder of cryptically-named files with no notes turns it into a treasure hunt. Delivery is the last mile of the job: label it, sync it, back it up, and hand it over with a map.</div>

<div class="callout">
  <div class="callout-label">◆ From the set</div>
  <p>The kindest, most professional thing a sound recordist can do is write a short note to the editor at the end of the shoot — plain English, not jargon. "Scene 8, take 2 is the clean one; take 4 has a motorbike. The lav on the lead cut out in Scene 12, so use the boom. Room tone for each location is in the TONE folder, wild lines in WILD." Five minutes of writing that saves the editor a day of detective work and rescues takes they'd otherwise have written off as unusable. Great sound that nobody can find isn't great sound. Hand it over with a map.</p>
</div>`,
